Title: The Monkey's Paw
Credit: Screenplay adaptation of
Author: W.W. Jacobs's short story (1902, public domain)
Draft date: 7/18/2026
Notes: Substituted for "The Lottery" (Shirley Jackson, 1948), which remains under copyright and could not be adapted. This story is genuinely public domain.

====

FADE IN:

INT. WHITE FAMILY PARLOR - NIGHT

A cozy, modest room. Rain lashes the windows. MR. WHITE (60s) and his son HERBERT play chess by the fire while MRS. WHITE knits nearby.

MR. WHITE
(studying the board)
Hark at the wind.

A firm knock at the door. Herbert answers, admitting SERGEANT-MAJOR MORRIS, weathered and sun-browned from years abroad, stamping rain from his coat.

MR. WHITE (CONT'D)
(delighted)
Morris! Come in, come in, out of that wet.

CUT TO:

INT. WHITE FAMILY PARLOR - LATER

Morris, several drinks in, grows quieter and stranger as the evening wears on, the family pressing him for stories of India.

MR. WHITE
You were saying about a monkey's paw or something, Morris.

SERGEANT-MAJOR MORRIS
(subdued, reluctant)
Nothing. Leastways, nothing worth hearing.

MRS. WHITE
(curious)
Monkey's paw?

Morris draws a small, withered paw from his pocket, dropping it on the table as though it burns him.

SERGEANT-MAJOR MORRIS
It's just a bit of what you might call magic, perhaps. An old fakir put a spell on it. He wanted to show that fate ruled people's lives, and that those who interfered with it did so to their sorrow.

He explains, haltingly, that the paw grants three wishes to three separate men, but at a terrible price -- one he will not fully describe.

MR. WHITE
(intrigued, reaching for it)
Well, why don't you have three, sir?

SERGEANT-MAJOR MORRIS
(grim)
I have had my three.

HERBERT WHITE
And did you really have the three wishes granted?

SERGEANT-MAJOR MORRIS
(quietly)
I did.

MRS. WHITE
And has anybody else wished?

SERGEANT-MAJOR MORRIS
(after a long pause)
The first man had his three wishes. Yes. I don't know what the first two were, but the third was for death. That's how I got the paw.

A heavy silence. Morris suddenly seizes the paw and moves to throw it on the fire.

MR. WHITE
(stopping him)
If you don't want it, Morris, give it to me.

SERGEANT-MAJOR MORRIS
(reluctant, finally relenting)
I won't. I threw it on the fire once already tonight. If you keep it, don't blame me for what happens. Pitch it on the fire again, like a sensible man.

Mr. White pockets the paw despite the warning. Morris leaves soon after, uneasy.

CUT TO:

INT. WHITE FAMILY PARLOR - LATER THAT NIGHT

Herbert, half-mocking, half-curious, eggs his father on.

HERBERT WHITE
(grinning)
Well, don't waste it, father. Wish for two hundred pounds -- that'll just clear the house, and you'll be well square with the world.

Mr. White holds the paw aloft, feeling faintly foolish under his family's amused gaze.

MR. WHITE
(half-serious)
I wish for two hundred pounds.

The paw TWITCHES violently in his grasp. Mr. White cries out and drops it, staring at his hand.

MR. WHITE (CONT'D)
(shaken)
It moved. As I wished, it twisted in my hand like a snake.

HERBERT WHITE
(laughing it off)
Well, I don't see the money, and I bet I never shall.

They retire for the night, uneasy despite the joking.

CUT TO:

EXT. WHITE HOUSE - GARDEN GATE - MORNING (NEXT DAY)

Herbert leaves for his work at the factory, waving cheerfully back at his mother.

CUT TO:

INT. WHITE FAMILY PARLOR - LATER THAT DAY

Mrs. White knits by the window. A well-dressed STRANGER hesitates at the garden gate outside, seeming reluctant to approach.

MRS. WHITE
(calling to Mr. White)
There's someone at the gate -- and he seems in no hurry to come to the door.

The stranger finally enters, avoiding their eyes, his manner grave and careful.

STRANGER
(gently, formally)
I've been asked to call by Maw and Meggins.

Mr. and Mrs. White exchange a glance -- that is Herbert's employer.

MRS. WHITE
(suddenly afraid)
Is anything the matter? Has anything happened to Herbert?

STRANGER
(unable to meet her eyes)
I'm sorry --

MRS. WHITE
(rising, desperate)
Is he hurt?

STRANGER
Badly hurt. But he is not in any pain.

MRS. WHITE
(collapsing into a chair)
Thank God for that! Thank God for --

She stops, catching the stranger's expression, and understands.

STRANGER
(quiet, final)
He was caught in the machinery.

A long, terrible silence.

STRANGER (CONT'D)
(carefully)
The firm wish me to convey their sincere sympathy with you in your great loss. As an acknowledgment of Herbert's services, they wish to present you with a certain sum as compensation.

MR. WHITE
(hollow, staring at nothing)
How much?

STRANGER
Two hundred pounds.

Mrs. White SCREAMS. Mr. White, ashen, catches her before she falls, staring at his own hand as though it were a stranger's.

FADE OUT.

CUT TO:

INT. WHITE FAMILY PARLOR - NIGHT (DAYS LATER)

The house is dark and cold, the fire nearly dead. Mr. and Mrs. White sit in silence, wrecked by grief. Mrs. White suddenly sits upright, eyes wide.

MRS. WHITE
(urgent, rising)
The paw! Where is the paw?

MR. WHITE
(alarmed)
It's downstairs, on the bracket. Why?

MRS. WHITE
(desperate)
We've only had one wish, Herbert -- only one wish out of the three! Go down and get it, quick, and wish our boy alive again!

MR. WHITE
(horrified)
Good God, you are mad!

MRS. WHITE
(seizing his arm)
Get it! Get it quickly, and wish! Oh, my boy, my boy!

Against every instinct, Mr. White fetches the paw. His hand trembles as he raises it.

MR. WHITE
(dread thick in his voice)
I wish my son alive again.

The paw falls to the floor. Nothing happens. Mrs. White stands at the window, staring out into the dark, waiting.

CUT TO:

INT. WHITE FAMILY PARLOR - NIGHT (LATER)

The candle has guttered low. A slow, deliberate KNOCKING begins at the front door -- soft at first, then harder, insistent.

MRS. WHITE
(overjoyed, rushing for the door)
It's Herbert! It's Herbert!

Mr. White, gripped by a horror he cannot name, blocks her path.

MR. WHITE
(frantic, low)
What are you going to do? Think, Mrs. White -- think of what may be at that door, coming from where he's been these ten days, changed by the machinery that took him.

MRS. WHITE
(struggling against him)
He's my son! I'm not afraid of my own son!

The knocking grows louder, more insistent, shaking the door in its frame. Mr. White scrambles on the floor in the dark, searching frantically for the fallen paw as his wife wrestles the bolt free.

MR. WHITE
(finding it at last, desperate)
The paw! Where's the paw?

MRS. WHITE
(at the door, sobbing with joy)
Let me get to him!

She throws the bolt and drags the door open. The knocking stops instantly. Cold night air and empty darkness beyond -- nothing on the step at all.

Mr. White, having found the paw at last, gasps out his final wish under his breath as his wife's cry of grief echoes down the empty street.

They stand together in the doorway, staring at the silent, empty road, illuminated only by a distant, flickering streetlamp.

FADE OUT.

> THE END <
